What qualities make Novak Djokovic so dominant at tennis? With a bonus discussion of Data Science, Tennis, and Basketball.¶

In the year 2021, Novak Djokovic has dominated the ATP tour, winning the first three grand slams to equal his career rivals, Rafael Nadal and Roger Federer at 20 grand slams each. In this document, we will examine attributes in Novak Djokovic's game by utilization of "The Data Science Pipeline". This pipeline is comprised of 5 stages: 1. Data Collection, 2. Data Management, 3. Exploratory Data Analysis, 4. Machine Learning, and 5. Communication of Insights Attained.

Section 1: Data Collection¶

The data below is extracted from 4 tsv files that were acquired from this website http://www.tennisabstract.com/cgi-bin/leaders.cgi?f=s00w1. The four datasets are read into a panda dataframe and then merged to create one main dataframe.

Section 2: Data Management¶

The data obtained from the TSV file is fairly tidy but there are some changes we have to make before we can effectively run analysis on the data. First, the percentage signs that occur in elements of some columns need to be removed, because otherwise these columns will not be able to be used. Second, these same elements from columns with percentage signs are currently string values and need to be changed to be float values. There is fortunately no missing data.

Section 3: Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In our dataframe, the column named M W% stands for match winning percentage. Since winning matches is the outcome that makes Novak Djokovic so successful, it can be viewed as our dependent variable. We are going to create a correlation matrix between the columns of the dataframe, and will examine specifically how the different columns correlate with match winning percentage. The correlation matrix is displayed using Seaborn, a useful statistical data visualization library, via the heatmap function.

In [7]:
plt.subplots(figsize = (30,30))
g = sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot = True)

g.set_title("Correlation Matrix of Tennis Dataframe Columns")
Out[7]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Correlation Matrix of Dataframe Columns')

The heatmap above shows the correlation coefficients between all column variables in the tennis dataframe. This coefficient, named the r value, ranges from [-1,1] which 0 to 1 is measuring how strongly positively correlated the two variables are, and 0 to -1 is measuring how strongly negatively correlated the two variables are. Correlation coefficients between 0.0 and 0.3 have a weak correlation, between 0.3 and 0.5 have a correlation, between 0.5-0.7 have a moderate correlation, and between 0.7-1.0 have a strong correlation. We will examine variables than have a correlation greater than 0.5 with match winning percentage, M W%. These variables are listed below, along with their respective correlation coefficients with match winning percentage. Some variables that have a moderate or high correlation with match winning percentage were removed do to a duplicate nature. For instance Bks/S: Return Games Won per Set was used so Bks/M: Return Games Won per Match was removed.

M, Matches Played: 0.51

SPW, Percentage of Service Points Won: 0.67
2nd%, Second Serve Points Win Percentage: 0.70
Hld%, Hold Rate, Percentage of Service Games Won: 0.68
Pts/SG, Points Played per Service Game: -0.67
PtsL/SG, Points Lost per Service Game: -0.70
BPConv, Break Points Opportunities Converted: 0.64
BPChnc, Break Point Chances: 0.61
Bks/S: Return Games Won per Set: 0.5
BPSvd%: Percentage of Break Point Saved while Serving: 0.56
BPvs/G: Break Points Faced per Game: -0.63
Bkn/S: Service Games Lost per Set: -0.71

Section 4: Machine Learning¶

In this section we are going to use machine learning to find the linear regressions between match winning percentage and the various variables it is moderately to highly correlated with, listed above. An import aspect of data science and the data science pipeline is understanding how to leverage helpful libraries in order to accomplish desired tasks. In this section we are going to use sklearn, a machine learning library, in order to find these linear regressions. The function used to create a linear regression model is sklearn's linear_model.LinearRegression() and that model can be fit with columns from the tennis dataframe to create the linear regression. It is highly recommended that the reader looks into documentation for sklearn if they are curious about its capabilities and other machine learning tasks that sklearn can accomplish. A critical aspect of data science is being comfortable with documentation and it is an extremely helpful resource! https://scikit-learn.org/stable/user_guide.html

Additionally we'll be using another data visualization library named matplotlib, in order to create scatter plots and their respective linear regressions for plots Match Winning percentage vs "Variable X" where variable X is the correlated variable.

It is evident from the scatter plots with linear regressions that Novak Djokovic excels in a number of various aspects in his game. For every graph, the point representing Djokovic is sitting well above the linear regression line. To further our analysis of this data we are going to step away from examining Djokovic and look at these variables as a grouping. To this point we have created single linear regressions in regards to the correlations between match win percentage and a variety of other variables it is moderate to highly correlated with. These other variables have been treated as independent variables, and we are going to try to see if they are truly independent, which would allow for us to use multiple linear regression to represent match win percentage and the variable it depends on. We will plot another correlation matrix through a seaborn heatmap, this time using the reduced column variables. This will have the same information as the correlation matrix in section 3, but will be more readable and easier to compare all variables in the matrix instead of focusing on a single column. In order to accomplish this, a subset of the tennis dataframe will be created.
